Freshman In-Person Visit Nights

Tuesday, September 1st, 2020 6:30-8pm
Wednesday, September 2, 2020 6:30-8pm

On September 1 and 2, we would like to invite the class of 2024 to visit BFUHS, practice all of our hybrid procedures, have a brief presentation in the auditorium, collect their Chromebooks (and return their existing Chromebook if they have one from BFMS), and class T-shirts. On Tuesday 9/1 all students and their parents with surnames A-K will attend and on Wednesday, 9/2 students and their parents with surnames L-Z will attend. We look forward to seeing you at our front door on your designated evening.

Order:
Screening
Move to Block One class
Look at some other classrooms
Move to the Auditorium (presentation)
Move to the Cafeteria (Chromebook return and distribution)

post_text:
Below are some resources for families who may need childcare support.

Families can access child care through the state-wide child care referral network. Child Care Referral Specialists at statewide Community Child Care Support Agencies can match families with available child care options, including for school-aged children. There is no charge for this service, and it is available to all Vermonters. For more information: https://dcf.vermont.gov/cdd/cccsa

Families can receive financial support for child care by talking with an eligibility specialist. The Child Care Financial Assistance Program helps families pay for child care. Families with a household of four people can make up to $77,256 per year and qualify for help. Eligibility specialists maintain an ongoing connection with families who receive this benefit and help them as their needs change. For more information:

https://dcf.vermont.gov/benefits/ccfap

BFUHS Indoor Track team finds success at Vermont DII State Meet! Abby Broadley, grade 10, ran away with the victory in the women‚Äôs 3000m - setting a new VT State Record with a time of 10:28.63! Jonathan Carrington, grade 12, also claimed first in the men‚Äôs shot put with a distance of 12.84m! The women‚Äôs 4 by 800m relay team, comprised of Stephanie Ager (10), Molly Hodsden (11), Maya Waryas (10) and Abby Broadley (10) finished in second place with a time of 10:49.21 and Stephanie Ager also finished in third place in the women‚Äôs 1500m with a time of 5:16.16!
Congratulations to these amazing student-athletes, the rest of the BFUHS Indoor Track team and to Coach Bennett and Coach Ferenc!
text:
BFUHS Indoor Track team finds success at Vermont DII State Meet! Abby Broadley, grade 10, ran away with the victory in the women‚Äôs 3000m - setting a new VT State Record with a time of 10:28.63! Jonathan Carrington, grade 12, also claimed first in the men‚Äôs shot put with a distance of 12.84m! The women‚Äôs 4 by 800m relay team, comprised of Stephanie Ager (10), Molly Hodsden (11), Maya Waryas (10) and Abby Broadley (10) finished in second place with a time of 10:49.21 and Stephanie Ager also finished in third place in the women‚Äôs 1500m with a time of 5:16.16!
Congratulations to these amazing student-athletes, the rest of the BFUHS Indoor Track team and to Coach Bennett and Coach Ferenc!

BFUHS members of Our Voices Exposed (OVX) teamed up with students from BFMS and staff from GFC today to celebrate the Great American Smokeout. Cigarettes are the most littered item on earth, accounting for 38% of all collected litter. Cigarette waste is toxic and the filters are made of plastic fibers.
Today these students cleaned up over 550 cigarette butts and JUUL pods, doing their share to clean up our environment!

Join the Dramatic Performance class for their annual murder mystery dinner. This year we will be presenting Trouble at the Talent Show. An All-School Talent Show leads to fierce competition between The Tiffanys, The Jocks, The Grungies, and The Regs (regular kids). The Lunch Ladies and Maintenance Guys are also in the show despite their bitter rivalry. Show Choir Director Sheryl and Drama Teacher Mark keep the show moving. But before the judging is complete, one contestant winds up out of contention! Complete with a dinner of lasagna, salad, garlic bread and dessert, along with audience participation with the chance to interrogate the suspects, this event is sure to be fun for the whole family!
Tickets are $16 in advance and $20 at the door. Availability at the door is limited, so purchasing tickets in advance is highly recommended.
Friday, April 7th at 6:00PM in the gym-side cafeteria

post_text:
"Oh, the thinks you can think" when Dr. Seuss's best-loved characters collide and cavort in an unforgettable musical caper! Bellows Falls Union High School Drama department presents Seussical, a fantastical, magical, musical extravaganza! The cast will lovingly bring to life all of our favorite Dr. Seuss characters, including Horton the Elephant played by Paulryan Chipman, The Cat in the Hat, performed by Jackson Purdy, Gertrude McFuzz, played by Zoe Schemm, lazy Mayzie, performed by Sophia Cardini, and a little boy with a big imagination--Jojo played by Emily Wunderle. The colorful characters transport us from the Jungle of Nool to the Circus McGurkus to the invisible world of the Whos.
Performances will be on Friday, March 18th at 7:00 p.m., then two shows on Saturday, March 19th at 2:00 p.m. and 7:00 p.m.

post_text: The third annual Windham Northeast Supervisory Union's Career Day will take place on Friday, April 10th, 2015 from 9:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m. in the Bellows Falls Union High School gymnasium. Students in grades 4-12 will spend time visiting employers from all career fields. WNESU's Career Day provides provides an opportunity for students to interact with professionals to gain first-hand knowledge and perspectives and perspective of post-secondary education and career options. The hope is that students will make meaningful connections between their education today and their work and career life tomorrow. Organizers have encouraged students to pepper employers with questions about the industry, the available jobs, educational requirements, and what the path to the career looks like.

Parents of Bellows Falls Union High School (BFUHS) students are invited to attend a special performance by guest speaker Matt Bellace. This event will take place on Wednesday, March 18th at 8:00 AM at the BFUHS Auditorium. Matt Bellace‚Äôs presentation to both students and parents will focus on natural highs and making healthy choices. For almost 20 years, Dr. Bellace has been traveling the country as a professional speaker and stand-up comedian. Dr. Bellace has a PhD in clinical neuropsychology, which is the study of the brain and behavior. He is the author of the book, ‚ÄúA Better High,‚Äù co-author of the National Geographic Series, ‚ÄúThis or That,‚Äù and was a regular on truTV‚Äôs, ‚ÄúWorld‚Äôs Dumbest.‚Äù
This event is sponsored by School-Based Substance Abuse Services (SBSAS) and Windham County Partnership for Success (PFS) Grants from the Vermont Department of Health in collaboration with Greater Falls Connections and Windham Northeast Supervisory Union.

'The Importance of Being Earnest', Oscar Wilde's madcap farce about mistaken identities, secret engagements, and lovers entanglements at the Bellows Falls Union High School on November 15th and 16th. In addition to the two traditional evening performances, the cast will perform at a school assembly as well as a matinee. The understudy cast, featuring Jon Skrocki, Brittany Laurendeau, Hollie Jackson, and Liz Brooks will perform at the student assembly which will be held on Friday November 15th during 4th block, as well as at the matinee to be held on Saturday November 16th at 2:00 p.m. in the Bellows Falls Union High School auditorium. The primary cast, featuring Austin McDaniel, Austin Ielpi, Sam Empey, Trinna Larsen, Emma Moyna, Paige Moody, Arianna Parris, Nieva Schemm and Anny Brown will perform in two evening shows on Friday November 15th and Saturday November 16th at 7:30 p.m. Admission is $5.00 at the door.

post_text: Students at Bellows Falls Union High School will welcome Darcy Frey, author of The Last Shot: City Streets, Basketball Dreams. The book was distributed to every student and faculty member for their summer reading assignment. The Literary Kick Off event will be scheduled as soon as possible, with the author coming to BFUHS to talk to students during the day, then an evening talk at 7pm at BFUHS. This event is free and open to the public. Frey will speak about his experience of writing about high school basketball, struggles and realities of life in the inner city, and the big business that is collegiate athletics. Information about Frey and his background can be found on the website of the Literary Kick Off (http://rockinghamlibrary.org/bfuhsliterary/litfrey.html).

March 25, 2013 at 8:50 AM ¬∑

The Bellows Falls Union High School's Drama Club is proud to present their spring musical, "The Pajama Game" on March 29th at 7:00pm as well as March 30th at 2:00 and 7:00pm in the BFUHS auditorium. The dangers of a work place romance are explored to hysterical effect in this romantic comedy. Conditions at the Sleep-Tite Pajama Factory are anything but peaceful, as sparks fly between new superintendent Sid Sorokin, played by James Morton, and Babe Williams, played by Paige Moody, leader of the union grievance committee. Their stormy relationship comes to a head when the workers strike for a 7 and a half cent pay increase, setting off not only a conflict between management and labor, but a battle of the sexes as well. General admission $5.

All BFUHS students, staff, and family and the public are invited to attend. Patrick covers a wide range of current pressing topics from bullying to substance abuse through an entertaining and informative presentation intermingled with break dancing. The performance is sponsored by the Greater Falls Prevention Coalition. For more information contact Logan Bonney, BFUHS SAP Coordinator at 802-463-3944 or visit the speaker's web site at www.patrickperez.org.

post_text: Nick Zachary spent many hours working after school with students during his 18 years of teaching math at the Bellows Falls Union High School. Now he's back at the high school doing what the loved most about teaching, working one on one with students who seek out extra help by visiting him in the Academic Support Room (ASR). He and Eric Bone, also a retired BFUHS teacher, opened the Academic Support Room last year for any and all students, from remedial to advanced, who seek out assistance.
